[Gemini]: I have analyzed the code in `pydantic/v1/networks.py` from line 116 to 167, which covers several flagged locations. I've identified two new regex patterns that are vulnerable to ReDoS.

1.  **`ascii_domain_regex` at line 146:** The regex compiled is `fr'(?:{ascii_chunk}\\.)*?{ascii_chunk}{ascii_domain_ending}'`. The component `ascii_chunk` is `r'[_0-9a-z](?:[-_0-9a-z]{0,61}[_0-9a-z])?'`. The combination of a repeating group `(?:...)*?` with a nested, bounded quantifier `{0,61}` inside it creates a pattern susceptible to catastrophic backtracking. An attacker could provide a long string of repeating subdomains like `"a.a.a.a.a.a.a.a.a.a.a.a.a.a.a.a.a.a.a.a."` that doesn't quite match the final parts of the regex, causing the engine to explore an exponential number of paths.

2.  **`int_domain_regex` at line 157:** This regex has the exact same vulnerable structure as `ascii_domain_regex` but uses a wider character set (`int_chunk`). The vulnerability is identical in nature.

Given that these functions are within a network validation module, it is highly probable that they are used to parse domain names from user-controlled input without prior length validation, consistent with the other vulnerabilities found in this package.

I will submit a single finding for the `ascii_domain_regex` vulnerability as it represents this class of issue. This is my final action.

